<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}-{3}{y}=-{13}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle-{6}{x}-{4}{y}={34}</m></p>
<p><input type="text" style="width:10.6ch" name="qn0" id="qn0" value="" autocomplete="off" aria-label="Question 1" class="text"/></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left(-{7},{2}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of --6. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle--\frac{{6}}{{1}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{-{6}}}{{1}}{\left({1}{x}+-{3}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{-{6}}}{{1}}{\left(-{13}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left(-{6}\right)}{x}+-{18}{y}=-{78}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{6}{x}-{4}{y}={34}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{22}{y}=-{44}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-\frac{{44}}{{-{{22}}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}={2}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}+-{3}{\left({2}\right)}=-{13}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}+{\left(-{6}\right)}=-{13}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}=-{13}-{\left(-{6}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}=-{7}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-\frac{{7}}{{1}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-{7}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left(-{7},{2}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>